# highlight-panel Component Implementation Guide

## Overview

The `highlight-panel` is a custom form component that extends the base `panel` (container) component. It provides visual feedback by highlighting any child field whose value changes, automatically removing the highlight from previously highlighted siblings.

## Features

- **Automatic child change detection**: Monitors all child field value changes
- **Visual highlighting**: Applies `.highlighted` class to the child wrapper when its value changes
- **Sibling deselection**: Automatically removes `.highlighted` from other children
- **Smooth transitions**: CSS animations for a polished UX
- **Works with all field types**: Compatible with any child field (text, number, checkbox, etc.)

## Component Structure

```
components/
└── highlight-panel/
    ├── highlight-panel.js       # Core logic with child subscription pattern
    ├── highlight-panel.css      # Styling for .highlighted state
    ├── _highlight-panel.json    # Authoring properties (extends panel)
    └── IMPLEMENTATION_GUIDE.md  # This file
```

## How It Works

### Architecture

1. **Parent Subscribe**: The component subscribes to the panel's model during `'register'` event
2. **Child Discovery**: Uses `model.items` to find all child field models
3. **Child Wrappers**: Resolves each child's DOM wrapper using `[data-id="${child.id}"]`
4. **Child Subscriptions**: Attaches a subscribe listener to each child with `{ listenChanges: true }`
5. **Value Change Detection**: When a child's value changes, the component:
   - Removes `.highlighted` from all sibling wrappers
   - Applies `.highlighted` to the changed child's wrapper

### Key Implementation Points

**From `highlight-panel.js`:**

```js
subscribe(fieldDiv, formId, (_fieldDiv, fieldModel, eventType, payload) => {
  if (eventType === 'register') {
    model = fieldModel;
    // Subscribe to each child field
    model.items?.forEach((child) => {
      const childWrapper = fieldDiv.querySelector(`[data-id="${child.id}"]`);
      subscribe(childWrapper, formId, (_el, _childModel, childEvent, childPayload) => {
        if (childEvent === 'change') {
          childPayload?.changes?.forEach((change) => {
            if (change?.propertyName === 'value') {
              // Remove highlight from all children
              fieldDiv.querySelectorAll('[data-id]').forEach((wrapper) => {
                wrapper.classList.remove('highlighted');
              });
              // Add highlight to this child
              _el.classList.add('highlighted');
            }
          });
        }
      }, { listenChanges: true });
    });
  }
}, { listenChanges: true });
```

**Critical pattern details:**
- Uses `[data-id="${child.id}"]` selector (not `#id`) to get the field wrapper
- Child subscriptions use the same `subscribe()` from `rules/index.js`, not `model.subscribe()`
- Always passes `{ listenChanges: true }` to receive `'change'` events with payload
- Checks `change?.propertyName === 'value'` to detect value changes only

### CSS Styling

The `.highlighted` class applies:
- **Light yellow background** (#fffacd) for visual prominence
- **Orange left border** (4px) for directional emphasis
- **Inset shadow** for depth effect
- **Smooth transitions** (300ms ease) for polished animations
- **Extra left padding** (12px) to accommodate the border

Customize the colors and styling in `highlight-panel.css` as needed.

## Using the Component

### 1. Add to form.json

Use `fieldType: "panel"` and add the custom `fd:viewType`:

```json
{
  "fieldType": "panel",
  "fd:viewType": "highlight-panel",
  "name": "my_highlight_panel",
  "jcr:title": "Customer Information",
  "repeatable": false,
  "items": [
    {
      "fieldType": "text-input",
      "name": "firstName",
      "jcr:title": "First Name"
    },
    {
      "fieldType": "text-input",
      "name": "lastName",
      "jcr:title": "Last Name"
    },
    {
      "fieldType": "email",
      "name": "email",
      "jcr:title": "Email Address"
    }
  ]
}
```

### 2. Build the form

```bash
npm run build:json
```

### 3. Deploy and test

Navigate to your form and interact with the child fields. When you change a field's value, its wrapper should highlight with the yellow background and orange left border.

## Behavior Examples

### Example: Three text fields in a highlight-panel

**Initial state:** No fields highlighted

```
[ First Name ] 
[ Last Name  ]
[ Email      ]
```

**After entering "John" in First Name:**

```
┌─[ First Name: "John" ] ◄── Highlighted (yellow + orange border)
│ [ Last Name  ]
│ [ Email      ]
```

**After entering "Doe" in Last Name:**

```
  [ First Name: "John"  ]
┌─[ Last Name: "Doe"   ] ◄── Highlighted (highlight moved here)
│ [ Email       ]
```

**After entering "john@example.com" in Email:**

```
  [ First Name: "John"      ]
  [ Last Name: "Doe"        ]
┌─[ Email: "john@example.com" ] ◄── Highlighted (now here)
```

## Customization

### Change highlight color

Edit `highlight-panel.css`:

```css
.highlighted {
  background-color: #e6f3ff;    /* Light blue */
  border-left: 4px solid #0066cc; /* Dark blue border */
}
```

### Add animation on highlight

```css
.highlighted {
  animation: highlightPulse 0.3s ease-out;
}

@keyframes highlightPulse {
  0% {
    background-color: #fff9e6;
    transform: scale(0.98);
  }
  100% {
    background-color: #fffacd;
    transform: scale(1);
  }
}
```

### Disable highlight removal from siblings

Modify `highlight-panel.js` to comment out the sibling removal:

```js
// Remove only the previous highlight (if you want to keep multiple highlights)
fieldDiv.querySelectorAll('[data-id]').forEach((wrapper) => {
  // wrapper.classList.remove('highlighted'); // Commented out
});
```

## Troubleshooting

| Issue | Solution |
|-------|----------|
| Highlight not appearing | Verify `fd:viewType: "highlight-panel"` is set in form.json |
| Highlight not changing on value change | Check browser console for errors; ensure child fields have `name` properties |
| Highlight only appears on first field | Check if `[data-id]` selectors are working; inspect DOM to confirm data-id attributes exist |
| Styles not loading | Ensure `highlight-panel.css` is in the component folder and properly compiled |
| Child subscriptions not firing | Verify `{ listenChanges: true }` is passed to all `subscribe()` calls |

## Testing Checklist

- [ ] Form loads without console errors
- [ ] Panel renders with all child fields visible
- [ ] Clicking/typing in first child highlights it
- [ ] Interacting with another child removes highlight from first child and applies to new child
- [ ] Styles (yellow background, orange border) are visible
- [ ] Transitions are smooth (no jarring color changes)
- [ ] Works with different field types (text, number, email, checkbox, etc.)
- [ ] Highlight persists when child field is disabled (if applicable)
- [ ] Repeatable panels (if applicable) each have independent highlight state

## Integration Notes

- **Component location:** `code/blocks/form/components/highlight-panel/`
- **Registered in:** `code/blocks/form/mappings.js` (added to `customComponents` array)
- **Base type:** `panel` (container component with `model.items` children)
- **View type:** `highlight-panel` (set via `fd:viewType` in form.json)
- **Child pattern:** Panel-based (uses `model.items` + `[data-id]` lookup + child subscriptions)

## References

- [SKILL.md](../../../SKILL.md) - Custom Component Creator skill documentation
- [references/custom-form-components.md](../../../references/custom-form-components.md) - Architecture guide
- [references/field-html-structure.md](../../../references/field-html-structure.md) - Panel HTML structure
- [references/subscribe-api.md](../../../references/subscribe-api.md) - Subscribe API and child subscription patterns

